Habitat: Adults migrate to the open ocean. Juveniles in coastal marine waters or large inland freshwater streams. Larvae in pools and eddies over silty mud to sand bottoms.
Notes: These lamprey adults leave the ocean and ascend streams in the late spring and early summer to spawn in shallow water over gravel nests. They die soon after spawning. The larvae live in the stream for five to six years before entering the ocean, where they become parasitic on various fish for one to two years.
Predators: Herons, gulls, seals, and sea lions.

Habitat: In oceans to depths of 3000ft or more, along coasts in estuaries and fresh water. Larvae in pools of creeks rivers or estuaries over silty mud to sand bottoms.
Notes: Sea lampreys thrive in systems where waterways lack obstructions (damsn or waterfallw), clean sand and gravel, sand beds free of pollutants with a large supply of organic matter, and large waterways with plentiful fish supply to serve as hosts. The larvae remain in freshwater or estuarine areas for four to five years before they transform into adults and enter the ocean. The introduced population in the Great Lakes is landlocked and completes its entire life cycle in inland waters.
Predators: Humans, trout, whitefish, chubs, burbot, walleye, and catfish.

Habitat: Close inshore from WA northward southward to depths of nearly 3000ft
Notes: All chimaerids deposit their eggs, which are fertilized internaly, in elongate ridged brown cases. Care should be taken in handling them, as the venomous spines can cause a painful wound, and the clasping organs are quite sharp. Most commonly are found living near the sea floor in sandy, muddy, or rocky reef environments.
Diet: Crabs, clams, shrimp, and sea stars.

Habitat: Bays over soft bottoms and off open coasts to depths of 150ft. Benthic animals associated with continental shelves.  Smaller individuals prefer to inhavit shallow, coastal waters and are commin in shallow bays near shores and estuaries.
Notes: Can be quite abundant in coastal range.
Diet: Sharks, rays, chimearas, dolphins, seal, fish, and mammals.
Predators: Great white sharks and killer whales.

Habitat: Temperate coastal waters over soft bottoms to depths of 1200ft.
Notes: Can be abundant and may be considered a pest. Can form large schools of hundreds of sharks.
Diet: Bony fish, smaller shakrs, octopus, squid, crabs, and eggs.

Habitat: Neer reefs over sand or mud to depths of 600ft. Often found on continental shelf in littoral zones, in shallow bays, in sand channels, and in kelp forests.
Notes: Generally found in shallow waters. They partially bury themselves during the day, and actively hunt at night.
Predators: Great white shakrs, broadnosed sevengill sharks, and humans.

Habitat: Inshore often on shallow sand flats in channels and around coral reefs. Adults are more wide-ranging, inhabiting deeper reefs, around bridges, rocky areas, and boulders.  Juveniles are more often found in crevices in shallow lagoons.
Notes: Sometimes seen resting, motionless on the bottom.
Diet: Small fish, sea urchins, and a variety of crustaceans.

Habitat: Surface of coastal waters mostly in warm- and cold-temperate latitudes.
Notes: They are notorious for short, fas chaes and are sometimes seen breaking the surface of the water in impressive jumps.
Diet: Seals, dolphins, whale carcasses, and squid.

Habitat: Shallow bays over sand and mud to depths of 300ft. Temperate shallow bays and estuaries provide the ideal habitat.
Notes: Travel in schools. They spend their days near the surface and the nights at greater depths. Harmless to humans.
Diet: Fish, eggs, crabs, shrimp, and clams.
Predators: White sharks, sevengill sharks, and humans.

Habitat: Inshore never far from land ascends large rivers for considerable distances.
Notes: They occasionally occupy rivers. They can be found in ocean inlets where saltwater meets freshwater, and are the only shark species that can tolerate prolonged periods in freshwaters environments. Bull sharks will give birth in estuaries and the young will remain in the estuary until temperatures drop seasonally. Considered aggressive.
Diet: Catfish, stingrays, fish, birds, and turtles.

Habitat: Commonly found close to shore, in estuaries as well as river mouths. They are also found in shallow muddy bays, mangrove swamps of high salinitiy, and lagoons.
Notes: Known to leap out of the water and spin before landing. Fast swimming sharks that often travel in schools.
Diet: Fish, skaes, rays, squid, crabs, and lobsters.

Habitat: Inshore and over bottoms of shallow bays and estuaries. Commonly found over muddy or sandy bottoms in shallow coastal waters such as bays, estuaries, habrods, or the mouths of rivers.
Near surface of coastal and offshore waters. Have been documented in river estuaries and harbors.
Notes: Voracious and dangerous. Moves in an S shaped fashion. Solitary.
Diet: Mollusks, birds, snakes, crustaceans, turtles, and manatees.

Habitat: Over bottom in surf zone to depths of about 120 ft. Commonly found under sand or mud, in intertidal shallow waters.
Notes: Reported to deliver 37 volts, but it is unlikelty that the eletric organ is used as an offensive weapon.
Diet: Worms, eels, small fish, and various crustaceans.

Habitat: Estuaries, lower parts of large rivers, and shallow coastal waters.
Notes: Sawfishes slash their saw-like snout from side to side among schooling fish in order to stun or kill them.

Habitat: Over soft bottoms at depths of 10-360ft. Occurs in coastal bays, estuaries, and over the continental shelf, usually on sandy or muddy bottoms, but occasionaly on low strands of kelp.
